# **1. Project Overview and Research Motivation**

This document records the complete technical work undertaken during Phase 1 of a systematic research project into Federal Reserve communication and its relationship with rate-sensitive futures markets. It covers every coding decision, every error encountered, and every fix applied, in the order they occurred.

The central research question is: does the tone of FOMC post-meeting statements contain information about subsequent moves in futures markets that is not already reflected in prices at the time of release? To answer this, the first requirement is a reliable, machine-generated score for every FOMC statement going back to 1994.

Phase 1 builds the scoring engine using a Loughran-McDonald financial dictionary baseline. This baseline is intentionally simple. The point is not that it will be the final answer, but that it provides a benchmark against which LLM-based scoring (Phase 2) can be compared and validated.

| **Why this matters for the paper** The dictionary baseline captures some real signal (2022 hiking cycle, 2019 cuts) but fails on others (2018 hiking cycle, 2016 liftoff). These failures are not problems to hide. They are the paper's core motivation. An LLM reads context; a dictionary counts words. The December 2015 statement said 'accommodative' repeatedly even while raising rates for the first time in nine years, which is linguistically confusing for a word list but trivially obvious to a language model. |
| --- |

